n to the media (another sibling indicated that some of the kids play video games all day long) to raise? Schools, at least, are managed and controlled by regulatory institutions and are subject to oversight. Our media and marketers who produce video games...not so much. &#10;In spite of the many critiques we can legitimately make about public schools, our good schools do a stellar job and even most mediocre institutions overcome the illiteracy and innumeracy Josh describes. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="782" language="en" documentId="362" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="SuburbanCat" date="7/29/2013 1:09 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375096179-786-56" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="362" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="578"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="579" end="782"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>